{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564287"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:11:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:11:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16963"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.19,0.56,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92100"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of heavy menstrual bleeding. She reports soaking through a pad or tampon every two to three hours during the first three days of her cycle, leading to times of embarrassment and she has started to avoid going out during these days. Her periods are regular with a 28-day cycle. She is planning to conceive in the next few months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Her complete blood examination shows haemoglobin 125 g/L (115-160), ferritin 25 \u00b5g/L (20-200), and normal coagulation profile. Transvaginal ultrasound shows normal uterine size and morphology with no fibroids or polyps.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Levonorgestrel intrauterine system","Endometrial ablation","Watchful waiting with iron supplementation","Tranexamic acid","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding (menorrhagia) with normal investigations, suggesting functional heavy menstrual bleeding. Given her desire to conceive soon, treatment options are limited to non-hormonal approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it is a non-hormonal medication that reduces menstrual blood loss by approximately 40-50%. It is taken only during menstruation and does not affect fertility or future pregnancy. It works by inhibiting fibrinolysis and stabilising blood clots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would effectively reduce menstrual blood loss but is contraindicated in this case as the patient is planning to conceive soon. It would need to be discontinued before attempting conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elevonorgestrel intrauterine system\u003C/strong\u003E is highly effective for heavy menstrual bleeding but would need to be removed before attempting conception and is typically recommended for women who have completed their family or want long-term contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in women who wish to preserve fertility as it permanently damages the endometrium and increases the risk of pregnancy complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting with iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate given the impact on her quality of life and the potential for worsening anaemia. Active management with tranexamic acid would be more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther non-hormonal options that could be considered alongside tranexamic acid include non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs during menses, which can reduce blood loss by 20-30% and help with dysmenorrhea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tranexamic acid is first-line medical therapy for heavy menstrual bleeding in women planning pregnancy.","Hormonal treatments are contraindicated in women actively planning pregnancy.","Normal pelvic ultrasound and blood tests suggest functional heavy menstrual bleeding rather than structural pathology."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Heavy menstrual bleeding [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Heavy-Menstrual-Bleeding.pdf","Leminen H, Hurskainen R. Tranexamic acid for the treatment of heavy menstrual bleeding: efficacy and safety. Int J Womens Health. 2012;4:413-21. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S13840. Epub 2012 Aug 17. PMID: 22956886; PMCID: PMC3430088."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"